# Animations: motion-v

This project uses [`motion-v`](https://motion.unovue.com/) (Motion for Vue) for animation work. **Do not** reach for Vue's built-in `<Transition>` / `<TransitionGroup>` — `AnimatePresence` wraps them with a richer, declarative API.

## When to use motion-v vs plain CSS

- **CSS `transition`** (with `--ease`, `--ease-qubic`, `--spring` tokens) — fine for trivial hover/focus state changes on a single property (`color`, `opacity`, `transform`).
- **motion-v** — entrance/exit animations, choreographed sequences, viewport-triggered (scroll), gestures, animating across `v-if` / `v-show`, variants across a subtree.

## Import & API style

Prefer the namespace API (`motion.div`) over `<Motion as="div" />` — it's terser and gives you HTML/SVG type completion.

```vue
<script setup lang="ts">
  import { motion, AnimatePresence } from 'motion-v'
</script>

<template>
  <motion.div
    :initial="{ opacity: 0, y: 20 }"
    :animate="{ opacity: 1, y: 0 }"
    :transition="{ duration: 0.4, ease: [0.8, 0, 0.16, 1] }"
  />
</template>
```

In Vue templates, **object props must be bound with `:`** and use **kebab-case** for multi-word props (`:in-view`, `:in-view-options`, `:while-hover`). `initial`, `animate`, `exit`, `transition`, `variants` are common enough to remember.

## Enter/exit with v-if or v-show

Wrap conditional elements in `<AnimatePresence>` so exits animate too:

```vue
<AnimatePresence>
  <motion.div
    v-if="isOpen"
    :initial="{ opacity: 0 }"
    :animate="{ opacity: 1 }"
    :exit="{ opacity: 0 }"
  />
</AnimatePresence>
```

- `:multiple="true"` when animating multiple siblings (uses `TransitionGroup` under the hood).
- `mode="wait"` to make the entering child wait for the exiting child.
- `mode="popLayout"` to let surrounding elements reflow immediately.
- `:unwrap-element="true"` when wrapping a component that renders its own wrapper (e.g. Radix `PopoverContent`).

## Viewport-triggered animations

```vue
<motion.div
  :initial="{ opacity: 0 }"
  :in-view="{ opacity: 1 }"
  :in-view-options="{ once: true, amount: 'some', margin: 100 }"
/>
```

`:initial="false"` skips the initial animation entirely (useful on SSR-hydrated content you don't want to re-animate).

## Gestures

Use `hover` / `press` props instead of CSS `:hover` / `:active` when the animation involves more than a single property or needs spring physics:

```vue
<motion.button
  :while-hover="{ scale: 1.05 }"
  :while-press="{ scale: 0.95 }"
  :transition="{ type: 'spring', stiffness: 260, damping: 20 }"
/>
```

## Variants for coordinated motion

When multiple elements should animate together, define `variants` once and trigger by name:

```vue
<motion.ul :initial="'hidden'" :animate="'visible'" :variants="list">
  <motion.li v-for="i in items" :key="i" :variants="item" />
</motion.ul>
```

## Wrapping custom components

```ts
import { motion } from 'motion-v'
import IconSquare from '~/components/Icon/Square.vue'

const MotionIcon = motion.create(IconSquare)
```

## Accessibility

`reset.scss` only neutralizes CSS animations under `prefers-reduced-motion: reduce`. motion-v runs in JS and is **not** affected by that rule — gate or shorten meaningful motion manually when reduced motion is preferred.
